<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>2 BANKS AGREE TO ERASE ZOMBIE DEBTS </strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Some of the nationâs biggest banks have come under fire for keeping debts alive on credit reports even when they were discharged in bankruptcy, essentially forcing borrowers to make payments on bills that they do not legally owe, as Jessica Silver-Greenberg of DealBook <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/11/12/debts-canceled-by-bankruptcy-still-mar-consumer-credit-scores/">reported last year</a>. Relief may finally be at hand for the consumers whose discharged debts have kept them from getting jobs or renting apartments, now that Bank of America and JPMorgan Chase have agreed to update borrowersâ credit reports within the next three months to reflect that the debts were extinguished, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/05/08/business/dealbook/bank-of-america-and-jpmorgan-chase-agree-to-erase-debts-from-credit-reports-after-bankruptcies.html">Ms. Silver-Greenberg reports in DealBook</a>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The agreement emerged this week in Federal Bankruptcy Court in White Plains, where the two banks, along with Citigroup and Synchrony Financial, formerly GE Capital Retail Finance, face lawsuits accusing them of deliberately ignoring bankruptcy discharges to fetch more money when they sell off pools of bad debt to financial firms. The banks are also being investigated by the United States Trustee Program, an arm of the Justice Department, about <b>whether the banks are deliberately flouting federal bankruptcy law</b>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In agreeing to ensure bankruptcies were registered on credit reports, Bank of America and JPMorgan Chase admitted no wrongdoing. A lawyer for JPMorgan Chase, according to court documents, said that by August the bank would ensure that all debts discharged in Chapter 7 bankruptcy were correctly recorded. <b>Bank of America promised to go further</b> by fundamentally changing the way the bank reports all the stale debts that are sold to financial firms. As for the other institutions, a spokesman for Citigroup said the bank has made a proposal âconsistentâ with what the other banks have proposed.<br />
</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>SYNGENTA REJECTS MONSANTOâS $45 BILLION BID</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The Swiss seed and insecticide maker Syngenta said on Friday that it had rejected an unsolicited takeover offer of more than $45 billion from Monsanto, its American rival, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/05/09/business/dealbook/swiss-insecticide-maker-rejects-takeover-offer-from-monsanto.html">Chad Bray reports in DealBook</a>. Syngenta said that its board of directors believed that the Monsanto bid undervalued âSyngentaâs prospects and underestimates the significant execution risks, including regulatory and public scrutiny at multiple levels in many countries.â </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Monsantoâs offer valued Syngenta at 449 Swiss francs a share, or about $490, and consisted of 45 percent in cash, Syngenta said. The offer valued Syngenta at more than $45 billion and represented <b>a 35 percent premium </b>to its closing price on Thursday. Syngentaâs shares rose 16.7 percent to 388.70 francs in early trading in Zurich on Friday after the company announced its rejection of the offer.<br />
</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>JONATHAN STEINBERGâS REBIRTH</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Second acts are rare on Wall Street, where the stigma of lost fortunes can linger, so when Jonathan L. Steinberg sold his failing business media company in 2001, his chances of a comeback were slim, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/05/08/business/dealbook/how-jonathan-steinberg-made-good-on-a-second-chance.html">Landon Thomas Jr. writes in DealBook</a>. Not only did he have to bear the burden of his own history, but he had to contend with investorsâ memories of the failures of his father, Saul, a noted corporate raider whose financial decline attracted wide scrutiny. But the younger Mr. Steinberg, also known as Jono, heeded his late fatherâs advice â to have the courage of his convictions â and the tiny stock indexing division that the younger Mr. Steinberg pulled from the ruins of his old firm has become one of the fastest-growing fund companies. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the first quarter of this year, Mr. Steinbergâs firm, WisdomTree Investments, which oversees $60 billion, took in more cash than any other asset management company save for the fund giants Vanguard and BlackRock. âJono has gone from <b>zero to $60 billion in less than 10 years</b>,â said Michael H. Steinhardt, the retired hedge fund pioneer who took a big stake in WisdomTree in 2004 and remains its chairman and largest shareholder. âThat is almost too good.â </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Arthur Levitt Jr., the former head of the Securities and Exchange Commission, says the younger Mr. Steinberg shares many of his late fatherâs good qualities, âand many better qualities on top of that.â And the father is not far from his sonâs mind: âI always saw myself running a publicly traded financial services company,â Mr. Steinberg said. âI am the product of my father â doing exactly what I expected to be doing.â<br />
</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>ON THE AGENDA</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The Bureau of Labor Statistics will release <b>monthly employment figures</b> at 8:30 a.m. <b>William C. Dudley</b>, president of the New York Fed, speaks at the Bronx Bankers Breakfast, which begins at 8:30 a.m.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>BRITISH POUND AND STOCKS GAIN ON ELECTION RESULTS</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The British pound and stocks climbed sharply in London in early trading on Friday after projections and partial results showed that Prime Minister David Cameron and his Conservative Party won a surprisingly solid victory in the British general election, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/live/uk-elections-2015/conservatives-win-pound-rises-and-markets-cheer/">David Jolly reports in The New York Timesâs live-blog coverage of the results</a>. The market reaction reflected relief among investors who had braced for days of uncertainty in the event of a muddled electoral outcome. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Analysts at Barclays said the market cheered âthe removal of substantial uncertainties and the likely introduction of policies generally believed to be more favorable to business.â The Barclays analysts said <b>the market rise could be short-lived</b>, however, as investors look toward threats to stability like the Conservative Partyâs plans for a referendum in 2017 on Britainâs membership in the European Union. They called the referendum âan event that is likely to generate a substantial amount of uncertainty, particularly if polls fail to show more substantial support for E.U. membership in the coming weeks and months.â The Wall Street Journalâs MoneyBeat blog also rounded up <a href="//blogs.wsj.com/moneybeat/2015/05/08/u-k-election-what-the-street-thinks-of-david-camerons-victory/">the opinions of top British fund managers and strategists.</a><br />
</p>
</div>
